snippet.title: How To Visit the Louvre Quickly and Efficiently
snippet.description:
A little guide on how to visit the Louvre, featuring my buddy Eddie. Find it helpful? Grab my new guide to Paris in PDF here: http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide Help me make more videos at http://patreon.com/jayswanson and then find me on the internet in all of the usual spots:
http://twitter.com/jayonaboat
http://instagram.com/jayswanson (me) http://instagram.com/mindofjayswanson (books)
http://facebook.com/jay.swanson.author

Music by: Dyalla

My name is Jay Swanson - I'm an American writer living in Paris on an artist visa and hoping to make the city of light my home base - at least for the foreseeable future. I write science-fiction and fantasy, vlog daily (when I'm not on a between-season break), and love pizza a little too much.

FAQ:
How long have you lived in France? On and off for over two years.

What do you miss most about ho- NACHOS

You're always talking about living on some ship. WHAT SHIP? - This ship: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MV_Africa_Mercy

Where are you from originally? Pullman, Washington - a small university/agricultural town near Idaho (and yes, the potatoes are amazing).

What do you film with? I currently film almost exclusively with my Samsung Galaxy S7: http://amzn.to/2sXEL4g

How do you get those shots where you're walking or running? A Joby Gorillapod for smartphones, like this: http://amzn.to/2sXNIL3

You drop your phone a lot, how does it survive? THIS CASE IS AMAZING: http://amzn.to/2hoxgTA

What do you edit with? Adobe Premiere - it's pretty much all I've ever used since high school.

Aren't you ever freaked out by leaving your camera behind to film yourself? Yep. But not too badly - I tend to be careful when I do.

Why are you living in #Paris? Because I've always wanted to. https://youtu.be/4Vivf6MqMxQ

But what are you doing there? https://youtu.be/ZW2RP--DO8Y

Do you speak French? Oui.

Do you make money off YouTube? Ha, no. I wish.

Can I come stay with you in Paris? - Have you seen my apartment? It's too small for me as it is! https://youtu.be/6t2qj3rdyX8

OK, but how do I use the Metro when I'm there? I made a handy video for you: https://youtu.be/T0YS5si8bJs

Ha-ha! You revealed the hushed Pont de Lions entrance. I used that entrance to visit often during my first time in Paris in 1975, it was a lifesaver and no one seemed to know about it. Great guide here to getting in without the major tourist hassles and planning to avoid the feeling of being overwhelmed by the sheer volume of artifacts.

The youth discount is available almost everywhere in the EU, but you need to ask for it and carry ID. Don't be put off by some museums that only discount to EU residents, they'll often extend the discount to others--including Americans--if the request is polite, includes a bit of local language (a "bonjour," or a "ya-sas" will open many doors and discounts as long as your children are standing with you and well-behaved).

My last visit to the Louvre was bringing the family in 2004 and our daughter wanted to see the Mona Lisa, which was directly up the stairs from the Pont de Lions entrance, looks like she's been moved to a much larger space. It was the first Sunday free entrance and it took all of 5 minutes to cruise in the Pont de Lions entrance while there were mile-long lines around the plaza waiting to enter through the I.M. Pei pyramid.

The Winged Victory of Samothrace is effing gorgeous. It's probably my favourite thing in the whole museum. Though there were some pretty fantastic paintings on the upper floors and the architecture is to die for.

I enjoyed The Wedding Feast at Cana while my friend braved the Mona Lisa crowds (I have no interest in the Mona Lisa as she's just famous for being famous). Google Arts teamed up with Tom Scott (another youtuber) about a year ago and did a pretty interesting video about The Wedding Feast at Cana. The painting was in a monastery (in Venice, I think) and stolen by Napoleon. Because of it's fragility (ex, it was cut in half at one point, which is why there's a horizontal seam), it wasn't repatriated. And, more recently, they did a digital scan which took 18 months to complete (3 months longer than it took to paint it - because museum digital scanning happens when the building is closed and is serious business).

I'm sure that's more than you wanted/needed to know, ha ha.

This was great! Too bad about Eddie's tools.

comments.textDisplay: Another nice video.  I remember my first time in the Louvre, October 2014.  I got there an hour before it opened w/my Museum Pass, 5th in line, headed straight to Mona Lisa when it opened, only about 10 of us in the room then I headed out.  I just followed the signs/pictures of Mona Lisa. I spent about 45 minutes walking through sections with only myself & security in the area.  I have a picture of me in front of a corridor connecting 7 rooms & it was only myself & security in each room.  June 2016, I was 3rd in line & only me & security in front of Mona Lisa for about 5 minutes.  Again, hit another part of the museum & had rooms to myself for a bit.  Cant wait to head back in Aug/Sep 2018.  Plan on seeing it during the late evenings that it is open during the week.

replies.textDisplay: I address this in a number of videos, but basically it's only polite to at least try to speak the language of the country you're visiting. If you make that effort, just by saying 'bonjour' when you enter a shop and learning how to ask if they speak English "parlez-vous anglais?" you'll find most do and many if not most are ready and willing to speak English with you. Entering anywhere with an attitude like they somehow owe it to you to speak your language, whether it's in France or anywhere else in the world, is frankly rude and unlikely to garner the results you're hoping for. You're basically guaranteeing yourself a bad time with your attitude if you refuse to be polite and make an effort of any kind while traveling. Hopefully you're not feeling quite as angry as your comment makes it sound - try to keep a positive outlook and have fun while you're visiting =)
